Calibration of Fisher’s exact test

I applied Fisher’s exact test to analyze the negative control data within the context of the undercover pipeline. First, I plot the p-values on a transfored scale.

Overall, the results look quite good. Fisher’s test exhibits good calibration far into the tail on all datasets except two: the Papalexi protein data and the Schraivogel perturb-seq data. Next, I plot the results on the untransformed scale.

We see some conservative p-values in the bulk of the distribution.

Positive control results

The Fisher exact test lags somewhat behind the other methods on the metric of power; however, the Fisher exact test does seem capable of making discoveries on positive control data.

Now, we explore the connection between (effective) sample size and power (as quantified by the number of Bonferoni rejections on the positive control pairs).

Plot p-value vs. sample size.

What happens when we remove the ~30% of pairs with effective sample sizes that are too small? Does calibration become OK?

Calibration after removal of pairs with small effective sample sizes

Effective sample size is simple to compute for the negative control analysis: for a given feature, simply count the number of negative control cells with nonzero expression.

ntc_effective_samp_size <- sample_size_df |>
  filter(grna_group == "non-targeting") |>
  group_by(response_id, dataset) |>
  summarize(effective_samp_size = sum(n_nonzero_cells))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'response_id'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Many of the pairs in our dataset have an effective sample size of below 250.

effective_samp_size_thresh <- 250
p <- ggplot(data = ntc_effective_samp_size,
       mapping = aes(x = effective_samp_size)) +
  geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(dataset~., scales ="free") +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Effective sample size") +
  ylab("Count") +
  scale_x_log10() + geom_vline(xintercept = effective_samp_size_thresh, col = "darkred")

First, here are the results on all pairs.

undercover_res_w_samp_size <- dplyr::left_join(undercover_res,
                                               ntc_effective_samp_size, by = c("response_id", "dataset"))
make_trans_qq_plot(undercover_res_w_samp_size)
